07051nam a22008295i 9780824878085DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20192019hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248780857 a10.1515/97808248780852doi  a(DE-B1597)513348  a(OCoLC)1098213504  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aHIS0080002bisacsh0485pa950qDE-1011 aPrazniak, Roxann, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSudden Appearances :bThe Mongol Turn in Commerce, Belief, and Art /cRoxann Prazniak; ed. by Anand A. Yang, Kieko Matteson. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (316 p.) :b16 color, 8 b&w illustrations, 4 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives on the Global Past00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION. Illustrating the Eurasian World in the Long Thirteenth Century (1206–1368) -- tPrelude to the Mongol Intervention in Eurasian History. A Brief Pre-Mongol History of Eurasia -- tCHAPTER 1. Tabriz in Azerbaijan (Ilkhanate) -- tCHAPTER 2. Constantinople in Rum (Byzantium) -- tCHAPTER 3. Siena in Tuscany (Land of the Franks) -- tCHAPTER 4. Cairo in Egypt (Mamluk Sultanate) -- tCHAPTER 5. Alchi in Ladakh (Greater Himalayan Region) -- tCHAPTER 6. Turfan in Uighurstan (Tarim Basin) -- tCHAPTER 7. Dadu in Khitai (Great Yuan) -- tCHAPTER 8. Quanzhou in Manzi (Great Yuan) -- tCONCLUSION. Theme and Variation in the Post-Mongol World -- tA Brief Chronology of the Long Thirteenth Century -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author -- tPerspectives on the Global Past0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn era rich in artistic creations and political transformations, the Mongol period across Eurasia brought forth a new historical consciousness visible in the artistic legacy of the thirteenth and fourteenth centuries. Historicity of the present, cultivation of the secular within received cosmologies, human agency in history, and naturalism in the representation of social and organic environments all appear with consistency across diverse venues. Common themes, styles, motifs, and pigments circulated to an unprecedented extent during this era creating an equally unprecedented field of artistic exchange. Exploring art’s relationship to the unique commercial and political circumstances of Mongol Eurasia, Sudden Appearances rethinks many art historical puzzles including the mystery of the Siyah Kalem paintings, the female cup-bearer in the Royal Drinking Scene at Alchi, and the Mongol figures who appear in a Sienese mural.Drawing on primary sources both visual and literary as well as scholarship that has only recently achieved critical mass in the areas of Mongolian studies and Eurasian histories, Roxann Prazniak orchestrates an inquiry into a critical passage in world history, a prelude to the spin-off to modernity. Sudden Appearances highlights the visual and emotional prompts that motivated innovative repurposing of existing cultural perspectives and their adjustment to expanding geographic and social worlds. While early twentieth-century scholarship searched for a catholic universalism in shared European and Chinese art motifs, this inquiry looks to the relationships among societies of central, western, and eastern Asia during the Mongol era as a core site of social and political discourse that defined a globalizing era in Eurasian artistic exchange. The materiality of artistic creativity, primarily access to pigments, techniques, and textiles, provides a path through the interconnected commercial and intellectual byways of the long thirteenth century.Tabriz of the Ilkhanate with its proximity to the Mediterranean and al-Hind seas and relations to the Yuan imperial center establishes the geographic and organizational hub for this study of eight interconnected cities nested in their regional domains. Avoiding the use of modern geographic markers such as China, Europe, Middle East, India, Sudden Appearances shifts analysis away from the limits of nation-state claims toward a borderless world of creative commerce.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aArtzEurasiaxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMongolsxHistoryyTo 1500. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh1 aMatteson, Kieko, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aYang, Anand A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2019z978311071956708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019z9783110606195oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065814940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780824878085zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824878085423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824878085/original  a978-3-11-061017-8  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-064982-6  Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  a978-3-11-065814-9  University of Hawaii Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-071956-7  DG Plus eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL